# YSK — End-to-End App Flow

Before building any feature, understand where it sits in this flow. Every page, action, and component maps to one of these steps.

---

## Step 1 — Admin signs up / logs in
- Clerk handles authentication (Google or email)
- On signup, Clerk webhook fires → syncs user to DB as `role: ADMIN`
- After login, admin is redirected to `/events`

---

## Step 2 — Admin creates an event
- From `/events`, admin opens the 4-step wizard:
  1. Event name (max 100 chars)
  2. Event type (Science Contest, Pitch Fest, Exhibition, etc.)
  3. Judging mode (Official Judge, Guest Judge, Public Voting, etc.)
  4. Review & confirm
- Event is saved to DB with status `DRAFT`
- Admin is redirected into the event dashboard

---

## Step 3 — Admin sets up categories & scoring criteria
- Admin goes to `/dashboard/class`
- Creates categories (e.g. Biology, Engineering, Chemistry) with a color
- Under each category, adds scoring criteria: name, description, max points, weight
- This becomes the **scoring blueprint** — every judge uses these criteria for projects in that category
- No judging can happen meaningfully without categories and criteria set up first

---

## Step 4 — Teacher submits a project (no account needed)
- Public page: `/submit/[eventId]` — zero auth required
- Teacher fills in:
  - School name
  - Teacher name + email
  - Project title + abstract
  - Category selection (with AI category suggestion shown automatically)
  - Uploads research PDF + optional poster images via UploadThing
- On submit:
  - Project is created in DB with `approved: false`
  - Status shows as **Pending** in admin dashboard
  - AI abstract summary is generated in the background and stored on the project

---

## Step 5 — Admin reviews submissions
- Admin sees all incoming projects in the dashboard table: school, teacher, category, status
- For each project, admin can:
  - **Approve** — project becomes eligible for judge assignment
  - **Reassign** — move to a different category if teacher selected wrong one
  - **Reject** — removes project from the event
- Judging assignments only happen after approval

---

## Step 6 — Admin invites judges & assigns projects
- From `/dashboard/management`, admin types a judge's email and clicks Invite
- Resend sends an email with a unique invite link (token stored in `JudgeInvite` table, expires in 7 days)
- Judge clicks the link → signs up via Clerk → enters system as `role: JUDGE`
- Admin then assigns specific approved projects to each judge
- One project can be assigned to multiple judges (scores are averaged)

---

## Step 7 — Judge logs in
- Judge lands on `/judge` — sees ONLY their assigned projects as cards
- Each card shows:
  - Project title
  - Category badge
  - School name (or anonymized code like `ENG-004` if anonymous mode is enabled in settings)
  - Status: Pending or Scored
- Judges cannot see other judges' assignments, scores, or any admin pages

---

## Step 8 — Judge scores a project
- Judge clicks a project card → `/judge/score/[projectId]`
- Page shows:
  - AI-generated abstract summary (from Step 4 background job)
  - Full abstract
  - Category criteria as sliders (0 to maxScore each)
  - Live total score updates as sliders move
  - AI score suggestions panel (judge can apply or ignore)
  - Notes/comments textarea
- Judge either:
  - **Save Draft** — saves progress, can return and edit later
  - **Submit Score** — locks the score, becomes read-only
- Once submitted, score cannot be changed unless admin explicitly resets it

---

## Step 9 — Admin monitors progress
- `/dashboard` shows live stats: total projects, scored, pending, judges active
- Projects table: school, teacher, category, current score, status
- `/dashboard/management` shows each judge's progress bar (scored / assigned)
- Admin can reset a submitted score if a judge made an error

---

## Step 10 — Leaderboard
- `/dashboard/leaderboard` ranks all projects by score
- If multiple judges scored the same project → final score = average of all submitted scores
- Admin can filter by category
- Leaderboard is **private by default** — admin toggles it public when ready
- Public leaderboard at `/results/[eventId]` shows rankings with no login required

---

## Step 11 — Event closes & results published
- Admin sets event status to `CLOSED`
- Judges can no longer submit scores after this point
- Admin can:
  - Export full results as PDF or CSV
  - Generate AI school feedback (per project, sent to teacher email via Resend)
  - Generate AI narrative report of the entire event
  - Publish the public results page at `/results/[eventId]`

---

## Key Rules Derived From This Flow

- A project cannot be assigned to a judge until it is `approved: true`
- A judge can only see projects in their `JudgeAssignment` records — never all projects
- Scores with `status: SUBMITTED` are locked — UI must be read-only for the judge
- Anonymous mode hides `schoolName` and `teacherName` from judges — show only `projectCode`
- `projectCode` is auto-generated on project creation (e.g. `ENG-004` = category prefix + sequential number)
- Leaderboard scores are always computed from `ScoreItem` averages — never a stored flat value
- After `EventStatus.CLOSED`, no new `Score` records with `status: SUBMITTED` should be accepted
- The `/submit/[eventId]` and `/results/[eventId]` pages are fully public — no Clerk auth
